00:43.020 --> 00:51.140
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. There are a number of awards given to
writers of science fiction and fantasy. The two best-known awards are the Hugo

00:51.140 --> 00:58.540
and the Nebula, both given annually. But the winners are selected in very
different manners. The Hugo is voted on by people attending the World Science

00:58.540 --> 01:06.560
Fiction Convention each year, so the selecting body would be made up mostly of
fans. And the Nebula is voted on only by members of the Science Fiction Writers

01:06.560 --> 01:15.080
of America, in other words, the writers themselves. The Hugo is the oldest
award. It was first given in 1953, and today there are a number of categories a

01:15.080 --> 01:24.540
writer can win in. He can win for a novel, a novella, a novelette, or a short
story. And there are also Hugos for movies, artists, editors, fan publications,

01:24.700 --> 01:34.000
and so forth. The Nebula began in 1966, so it's a more recent award. It's given
each spring at the annual banquet of the Science Fiction Writers of America. And

01:34.000 --> 01:42.680
that body consists of around 500 people, so the voting base for the award is
much smaller than it is for the Hugo. We asked one science fiction author, Jack

01:42.680 --> 01:53.440
Chalker, which award was the most prestigious. The Hugo, because it's been
around now so long, and it's had so much publicity, and it's been so well

01:53.440 --> 02:07.300
promoted by the industry, is generally recognized by the regular science fiction
book-line public, most of whom do not know how the Hugo was actually given. The

02:07.300 --> 02:18.620
fact is that I remember one Hugo winner who said that when she got on the train
to go home, she had her Hugo with her under her arm. She wasn't going to let it

02:18.620 --> 02:32.780
go. And the conductor on the train looked down and said, Isn't that a Hugo? So,
you know, in other words, basically, obviously the conductor reads science

02:32.780 --> 02:41.680
fiction. And he recognized the award, he just did not recognize. He didn't know
anything about how it was awarded or anything else, but he knew it was an

02:41.680 --> 02:54.560
enormously prestigious award. Therefore, putting Hugo award-winning author on
the front of a book means that these non-fans will recognize this as something

02:54.560 --> 03:08.100
single-out of exceptional. They will buy it. Because it's the best-known award,
Chalker says, it means a good deal of money to an author. It's worth quite a lot

03:08.100 --> 03:20.560
of money to someone who has not won one. I doubt it seriously whether it would
mean a dime to an Asimov, or an Arthur Clarke, or Robert Heinlein. You know,

03:21.360 --> 03:33.840
these people already have their wide market. But it means an awful lot to
particularly first-time winners. And it means that the publisher knows that by

03:33.840 --> 03:43.760
putting this on there, they're automatically going to have sales of two or three
times what they would have otherwise without even bothering to promote it. And,

03:43.840 --> 03:54.280
of course, you are going to promote it. It gives you promotion money as well.
Which means that I believe somebody's estimated that the minimum worth for Hugo,

03:54.520 --> 04:05.720
the minimum worth is around $50,000. Finally, we asked his opinion on the two
awards. Which would a professional writer like himself prefer to receive? I

04:05.720 --> 04:18.240
think the Hugo is more desired. I think the Hugo is, as I say, commercially
recognized. The Nebula, unfortunately, is... It sounds great. You know, it's an

04:18.240 --> 04:31.420
award given by the science fiction writers to themselves. But because it's such
a small group that does it, and because of an inordinately complex and

04:31.420 --> 04:42.300
ridiculous system of nominations and a lot of politicking, Oscar-style
politicking and everything else, it really boils down to cliques of friends

04:42.300 --> 04:53.660
being able to nominate themselves year after year. And the Nebula is quite often
won by a mere 40 votes. No matter which award a story may have won, Hugo or

04:53.660 --> 04:55.120
Nebula, it'll be a good one.

