05:56.360 --> 06:00.360
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:16.280 --> 06:21.580
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:24.320 --> 06:25.980
And here are your hosts.

06:30.520 --> 06:38.760
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. We produce the Science Fiction Radio Show
because we feel that science fiction and fantasy is the most exciting and

06:38.760 --> 06:46.580
significant literature of our time. And its popularity is more than obvious. Go
into any bookstore. You'll find that the science fiction section is the largest

06:46.580 --> 06:54.360
one there. And a science fiction movie, Star Wars, is the single greatest money
earner in Hollywood history, presently reaching toward a billion dollars gross.

06:54.980 --> 07:02.140
Our show is produced to keep you informed on what's happening in science fiction
and fantasy. We'll interview authors, for instance, both new ones and

07:02.140 --> 07:09.500
established ones. We'll review books and movies, previewing what will be coming
out, highlighting what's here now, and discussing significant work from the

07:09.500 --> 07:17.860
past. And we'll also talk with movie producers, agents, publishers, anyone
involved with science fiction and fantasy. And scientists, too. We'll

07:17.860 --> 07:25.660
occasionally interview people from NASA, for instance, and other scientists
working in areas such as robots and computers that current science fiction is

07:25.660 --> 07:26.180
dealing with.

07:32.160 --> 07:39.720
We feel that science fiction is not only an exciting literature of adventure and
escape, but we're convinced that it speaks to our present society in a vital and

07:39.720 --> 07:50.260
necessary way. A new and highly popular science fiction author, C.J. Cherry,
told us why she thinks science fiction and fantasy are valuable. The value of

07:50.260 --> 08:02.780
science fiction is essentially the broadening of vision. The broadening of
vision in time, because we do not really concern ourselves only with the future.

08:04.080 --> 08:19.460
This is why fantasy, which deals with past ages, has been quite as comfortable
in associating with science fiction as it has. On the one hand, it should seem

08:19.460 --> 08:30.460
very strange to find fantasy readers and science fiction readers trading books.
We'd think that we had nothing to say to each other. But in point of fact, we

08:30.460 --> 08:41.860
have all the world to say to each other. We have all of human experience to say
to each other. We have the long view, one sort of being the memory of mankind

08:41.860 --> 08:53.140
and the other being the hope and the aspiration of where we will go and what we
will do. Two sides of the same coin. Cherry also believes that science fiction

08:53.140 --> 09:05.860
and fantasy can put humanity into perspective, so to speak, can somehow show us
our place and our common unity. It's a kind of literature that widens the

09:05.860 --> 09:21.880
experience beyond one's daily life. It shows us the true size of the earth, the
true size of the universe, the true importance of our troubles, both the size

09:21.880 --> 09:35.060
and complexity of them and sometimes the extreme simplicity of them. It gives us
perspective in dealing with the world around us and with each other and shows us

09:35.060 --> 09:42.580
that we have, in many instances, a good deal more in common than we do in
difference.

09:50.040 --> 09:58.220
Another popular science fiction writer, Frederick Pohl, spoke to us on the value
of science fiction. Pohl has been in the field for some 50 years, not only as a

09:58.220 --> 10:07.320
best-selling writer, but as an agent, editor, and critic. He talks about one of
science fiction's unique attributes. I think science fiction has special

10:07.320 --> 10:16.400
qualifications to act as a vehicle for discussing anything that affects the
human being. It's a way of looking at the human race from outside objectively.

10:16.400 --> 10:26.360
It's a way of, it's a sort of game-playing mechanism for seeing what would
happen to human beings under conditions that haven't occurred yet but are very

10:26.360 --> 10:35.700
possible. And I think that that's probably one of the strongest factors
accounting for the continual growth and interest in science fiction that seems

10:35.700 --> 10:43.080
to have been going on as long as I've been alive. We'll continue next time with
some more views on science fiction and fantasy.

10:50.620 --> 10:58.620
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:58.620 --> 10:59.400
Odessa, Texas.

11:33.020 --> 11:42.540
Coming up next is the Science Fiction
Radio Show, so stay with us.

11:58.420 --> 12:03.760
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:06.540 --> 12:08.180
And here are your hosts.

12:13.180 --> 12:22.360
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. Why do people read science fiction? We asked
that question of two of science fiction's newest and most popular authors, Jack

12:22.360 --> 12:33.980
Chalker and C.J. Cherryh. Jack Chalker comments first. Why people pick up science
fiction and fantasy, I think, is because, first and foremost, because they want

12:33.980 --> 12:48.520
an escape. Because they really don't like, you know, I mean, you look at the
evening news, you read the papers, you know, 20 dead in El Salvador this

12:48.520 --> 12:58.980
morning. They're seeing 15 house fires set by mad arsonists downtown. Rape is
up. You know, all of this kind of thing. They're scared to go down the street in

12:58.980 --> 13:11.260
many of the cities and so on these days after dark. Seems like problems,
problems, problems. Unemployment lines. And then you can pick up science fiction

13:11.260 --> 13:23.360
or fantasy and you can jump into that other world. And you can become a part of
it and you can be something else, be somewhere else. So it's the ultimate escape

13:23.360 --> 13:33.680
literature. And, of course, once we've got you in the escape literature, then we
sneak in the serious stuff. C.J. Cherryh has many of the same ideas, but she

13:33.680 --> 13:44.240
provides a little different perspective in her answer. It's curiosity. It's a
wish to be in touch with one's environment, one's real environment.

13:47.200 --> 13:59.820
There are so many people who go through their daily lives concerned only with
what happens in the office and what happens around them. And it's sort of like

13:59.820 --> 14:16.880
being locked in one's cell if you never see beyond that. Nature and the universe
have so much more to it than what you perceive if you limit your vision to your

14:16.880 --> 14:20.560
immediate time and your immediate place and your immediate circumstance.

14:25.100 --> 14:31.260
And there's a certain nobility in ordinary daily affairs. It's

14:31.260 --> 14:41.800
the nature of the universe. I do not deny that. But I think that the real
understanding of what actually goes on in these ordinary daily affairs only

14:41.800 --> 14:53.660
comes through a wider understanding of the universe as a whole. And this is what
I think draws people to science fiction, to fantasy, to this whole vast realm of

14:53.660 --> 15:06.240
a romantical or positive way of looking at the universe, which has been in the
mainstream of thought since literature began.

15:12.180 --> 15:19.700
Both Cherryh and Chalker feel that science fiction or fantasy is almost
impossible to define. It's such a broad, all-encompassing form that it just

15:19.700 --> 15:29.260
can't be pinned down. Cherryh, however, offers some ideas on what science fiction
is. I think the best one that ever came up was Roger Zelazny's definition, at

15:29.260 --> 15:37.900
least I believe it's his, I don't know from whom he may have gotten it, but it's
basically that if I ever discover a definition of science fiction, I shall

15:37.900 --> 15:52.740
immediately attempt to violate it. Science fiction, to me, is a, will always
remain an experimental literature. It does not have rules, except to try to

15:52.740 --> 16:04.380
adhere to science and to true things as much as possible, and to try to have
your research well-founded in at least the best possible understanding of what's

16:04.380 --> 16:19.380
going on that you can arrive at. To me, science fiction is the same thing that
the unknown writer of the Gilgamesh epic did. A voyage in search of the unknown,

16:19.580 --> 16:26.420
this sort of literature. Next time, we'll talk to some writers who go back to
the pulp era of science fiction in the early part of this century.

16:33.900 --> 16:41.740
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:41.740 --> 16:42.500
Odessa, Texas.

