17:56.880 --> 17:58.500
And here are your hosts.

18:02.940 --> 18:12.440
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Joan Vinge began writing in 1974 and has
already won two Hugo Awards, one for the novella Eyes of Amber, and most

18:12.440 --> 18:21.100
recently for her novel The Snow Queen. The Snow Queen was Vinci's first full
-length novel, and she told us that it was quite an undertaking. That book was

18:21.100 --> 18:32.360
quite an incredible thing for me to write that book, because it wound up being
about, it was over 600 pages of manuscript. It's almost 200,000 words long. And

18:32.360 --> 18:43.120
when I started writing it, I had never written a complete novel all at once.
With Outcasts of Heaven, that was a novella, and then I had increased

18:43.120 --> 18:54.320
in size to that of a novel. And I was feeling kind of daunted about the very
idea of writing a normal, what I thought would be a normal-length novel of about

18:54.320 --> 19:05.620
200 pages. But I finally did sit down and start to write it. And the more I
wrote, the more I realized that it was not going to stop at 200 pages. I think I

19:05.620 --> 19:14.160
had gotten through 100 pages and realized that I had barely gotten into the plot
at all, my writing. And from then on, I could only just go on and write and

19:14.160 --> 19:21.640
write and write and write and see where it led me. It got more and more
complicated as it went along, until I really just stared at times that I would

19:21.640 --> 19:22.960
ever be able to finish the thing.

19:34.640 --> 19:42.420
As in a lot of science fiction, Vinge had to create the world on which the story
unfolds. This task required her to design a believable world and the people who

19:42.420 --> 19:51.440
populate it. She told us how she developed the background material for the main
city in the story and how some of the characters evolved. Well, I did a fair

19:51.440 --> 20:01.460
amount of background work beforehand, but actually I wound up doing a great deal
of the work, I think, during the process of writing the book. I had conceived of

20:01.460 --> 20:12.260
the idea of the wicked city of Carbuncle, which gets its name because it's
either a jewel or a fester, depending on your point of view. But I wanted it to

20:12.260 --> 20:22.860
be sort of a place where all kinds of cultures from all kinds of worlds came
together and mixed and mingled. And in trying to make a portrait of the city, I

20:22.860 --> 20:32.440
needed a lot of different characters with a lot of different backgrounds behind
them. And so whenever

20:32.440 --> 20:41.460
I needed a new character, I would write one into the story, and then I'd have to
figure out where they came from. So frequently I don't lay everything out before

20:41.460 --> 20:48.760
I actually start to write a book. I have kind of a basic structure, which I
think it was being sort of like a trellis, and then the story is a line that

20:48.760 --> 20:58.880
grows up through it and fills it in and flushes it out and things. She told us
that sometimes her characters take on a life of their own. One of the characters

20:58.880 --> 21:11.720
who comes from a very advanced society, the most technologically dominant
society in the book, started out as a walk-on character. His name is Gundhalinu,

21:11.780 --> 21:22.060
and he came along with one of the major characters in the book, in the scene,
and he just started acting up. And out of his personality, I kind of saw a whole

21:22.060 --> 21:30.900
cultural stereotype growing. And I realized actually part of where he came from
was that I had been reading a lot of books about, I've been reading some fiction

21:30.900 --> 21:39.780
books about Romans in Britain, because I've always been fascinated by Romans in
Britain as part of the archaeology thing, I guess. And just the kind of

21:39.780 --> 21:54.840
fascination was the sort of science fictional reversal, where the highly
cultured people are the people who too often wind up in sword and sorcery

21:54.840 --> 22:03.120
fantasies, the kind of dark and swarthy people. And they're usually spelunking
around in the bushes, but they were the people who were suave and sophisticated

22:03.120 --> 22:11.160
and on top, and the people with red hair and freckles and green eyes were
running around like howling barbarians in the brush. And I thought that was a

22:11.160 --> 22:15.540
delightful twist. Next time, more about the Snow Queen with Joan Vinge.

22:22.800 --> 22:30.800
