23:51.260 --> 23:59.060
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Last time we discussed how Joan Vinge
developed the background material for her award-winning novel, The Snow Queen.

23:59.060 --> 24:06.660
She did an elaborate job of laying out the locale over which her story took
place. She also had some very interesting characters for the reader to enjoy.

24:07.400 --> 24:15.640
Hans Christian Andersen wrote a fairy tale also called The Snow Queen. We asked
if she used a fairy tale as a basis for her novel. Yes, it is. As a matter of

24:15.640 --> 24:29.340
fact, that was my original inspiration for the book. There's a cartoon, an
animated movie of The Snow Queen, which they occasionally show on television. I

24:29.340 --> 24:37.740
was interested in it. You know, I had first seen that movie when I was in about
eighth grade and thought, oh, this is silly. But when I saw it again back during

24:37.740 --> 24:49.440
the 70s sometime, I realized what an interesting fairy tale it is. The thing
about most fairy tales is that they are frequently degenerate mythology. And if

24:49.440 --> 25:03.060
you know any particular amount about Near Eastern and European mythology, you
see a lot of symbolic archetypes. You see ravens and stags and the wicked

25:03.060 --> 25:14.380
stepmother and the sweet young innocent and things like that. Which, you know,
they all actually have their archetypes back in European and Near Eastern

25:14.380 --> 25:23.400
mythology. Vinge's interest in Andersen's fairy tale goes beyond his retelling
of an old myth. There were some specific concepts in his story that appealed to

25:23.400 --> 25:32.000
her. One of the criticisms of science fiction is its portrayal of women. While
designing a novel around the story in Andersen's fairy tale, Vinge chose to

25:32.000 --> 25:42.500
dispel some of those criticisms. She explains how. And the thing that interested
me especially about this particular tale was that there was no prince in it.

25:43.400 --> 25:52.020
It's usually prince who gets to do all the fun and exciting things like fighting
the dragons and things like that. And waking up the sleeping maiden and the

25:52.020 --> 26:02.020
women in the story are usually either the wicked old witch or some helpless
simpering creature. And, you know, I get sort of bored with that kind of thing.

26:02.080 --> 26:12.640
But I was very interested. This book was quite a twist because, or this fairy
tale was quite a twist because all the main roles in it were played by women.

26:13.160 --> 26:21.920
The basic idea of the story is that there are a little girl and a little boy who
are friends. And the little boy is stolen away by the Snow Queen, who is kind of

26:21.920 --> 26:31.360
an elemental goddess of winter. And most of the story concerns the little girl's
travels as she's searching for him and all the people she meets. And the people

26:31.360 --> 26:42.500
she meets are virtually all female. And the people in positions of power in the
story are women. And I thought that was quite interesting and unique. And I was

26:42.500 --> 26:54.400
in the mood to do a story in which women played major roles in the book. And so
I thought that was a good jumping off point for her. Vinge's background in

26:54.400 --> 27:01.280
archaeology is probably the reason why the societies and cultures of her
characters are so well developed. The background of a character usually holds

27:01.280 --> 27:09.960
the reasons and motivations for his or her behavior. Combine her background in
archaeology with a semi-mythical society, starships and high technology, a lost

27:09.960 --> 27:18.720
lover and the quest to find that lost lover, and you've got Joan Vinge's The
Snow Queen. She commented on what she was attempting when she wrote the story. I

27:18.720 --> 27:26.560
didn't want to write a fantasy, though. I didn't want to just make it a
retelling of the fairy tale, basically. I really wanted it to be a whole new

27:26.560 --> 27:34.560
story, and I wanted it to be science fiction as well, because that's just the
way my brain works, I guess. I have written a couple of fantasy stories

27:34.560 --> 27:45.200
recently, and I've always enjoyed reading fantasy as well as science fiction,
but so far the majority of my work has been at least technically science

27:45.200 --> 27:53.860
fiction. In The Snow Queen, Joan Vinge has displayed her depth as a writer. She
developed a complex society but retained an interesting storyline, and her story

27:53.860 --> 28:01.300
follows the main characters all over the galaxy without losing track of any of
them. Even though The Snow Queen is somewhat longer than most books, it easily

28:01.300 --> 28:07.320
holds the reader's attention. Vinge has done a fine job with her novel, and it
is well deserving of its high praise and awards.

28:15.120 --> 28:23.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

28:23.000 --> 28:23.780
Odessa, Texas.

